00:01:09.870 --> 00:01:10.800 align:middle line:90%
>>MITCH BATTROS: Thank you.

00:01:10.800 --> 00:01:13.050 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So tell us a little bit
about the solar flares-- what

00:01:13.050 --> 00:01:14.860 align:middle line:84%
exactly are they, how
do they originate,

00:01:14.860 --> 00:01:17.020 align:middle line:90%
and how do they affect Earth?

00:01:17.020 --> 00:01:20.580 align:middle line:10%
>>MITCH: Well, what
creates a solar flare is

00:01:20.580 --> 00:01:27.850 align:middle line:10%
when two opposing electrical
currents on the sun collide,

00:01:27.850 --> 00:01:31.540 align:middle line:10%
and when they collide,
or several of them

00:01:31.540 --> 00:01:36.940 align:middle line:10%
together, they explode out
into space in a twirling,

00:01:36.940 --> 00:01:38.890 align:middle line:10%
twisting, kind of
like a twister,

00:01:38.890 --> 00:01:40.710 align:middle line:10%
and that is what we see.

00:01:40.710 --> 00:01:44.100 align:middle line:10%
We see kind of an arc
and this stream of what

00:01:44.100 --> 00:01:45.920 align:middle line:10%
looks like fire that comes out.

00:01:45.920 --> 00:01:49.760 align:middle line:84%
That's the initial
wave that is initiated

00:01:49.760 --> 00:01:52.750 align:middle line:90%
from the connecting electrons.

00:01:52.750 --> 00:01:54.850 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: We have a picture
of that, actually.

00:01:54.850 --> 00:01:55.600 align:middle line:90%
>>MITCH: Oh, great

00:01:55.600 --> 00:01:57.270 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Kind of an idea of what
a solar flare would look like.

00:01:57.270 --> 00:01:59.690 align:middle line:84%
>>MITCH: That's what a
solar flare would look like,

00:01:59.690 --> 00:02:04.070 align:middle line:84%
and depending on the
size, it certainly

00:02:04.070 --> 00:02:07.910 align:middle line:84%
gives us an idea of what
effect that might have.

00:02:07.910 --> 00:02:09.900 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So there's
different sizes,

00:02:09.900 --> 00:02:11.380 align:middle line:90%
gradients of a solar flare?

00:02:11.380 --> 00:02:12.190 align:middle line:90%
>>MITCH: Yes.

00:02:12.190 --> 00:02:13.540 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK, what are those?

00:02:13.540 --> 00:02:16.815 align:middle line:84%
>>MITCH: The least amount
of powerful solar flare

00:02:16.815 --> 00:02:19.180 align:middle line:90%
is what's known as a C-Class.

00:02:19.180 --> 00:02:22.290 align:middle line:84%
A C-Class is still
significant, but it's

00:02:22.290 --> 00:02:26.782 align:middle line:84%
unlikely to create what's called
a geomagnetic storm with Earth,

00:02:26.782 --> 00:02:28.240 align:middle line:84%
if it happens to
be Earth directed.

00:02:28.240 --> 00:02:29.410 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: OK, so
that's the smallest.

00:02:29.410 --> 00:02:30.810 align:middle line:90%
>>MITCH: That's the smallest.

00:02:30.810 --> 00:02:33.750 align:middle line:84%
The next one would
be an M-Class flare--

00:02:33.750 --> 00:02:37.920 align:middle line:84%
you could say M for moderate,
and it can be very powerful.

00:02:37.920 --> 00:02:40.660 align:middle line:84%
That could does,
almost every time,

00:02:40.660 --> 00:02:42.750 align:middle line:84%
create a geomagnetic
effect when it

00:02:42.750 --> 00:02:46.930 align:middle line:90%
hits the Earth's magnetic field.

00:02:46.930 --> 00:02:52.200 align:middle line:84%
That's when you might see the
Aurora Borealis is often known.

00:02:52.200 --> 00:02:53.857 align:middle line:90%
The less-

00:02:53.857 --> 00:02:55.690 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: The most,
actually, the biggest one?

00:02:55.690 --> 00:03:00.390 align:middle line:84%
>>MITCH: Well, I going to
save the less incident that

00:03:00.390 --> 00:03:02.490 align:middle line:84%
could occur that's not
as pleasant as seen

00:03:02.490 --> 00:03:06.670 align:middle line:84%
a beautiful aurora, even an
M-Class flare could knock out

00:03:06.670 --> 00:03:07.710 align:middle line:90%
satellites.

00:03:07.710 --> 00:03:12.830 align:middle line:84%
It could also disrupt cellphones
related to the satellites

00:03:12.830 --> 00:03:14.880 align:middle line:90%
and have disruption.

00:03:14.880 --> 00:03:17.820 align:middle line:84%
And the X-Class,
the largest class

00:03:17.820 --> 00:03:21.640 align:middle line:84%
of the solar flares, that
can be really significant.

00:03:21.640 --> 00:03:26.920 align:middle line:84%
That is when the potential of
knocking out the satellites,

00:03:26.920 --> 00:03:30.470 align:middle line:84%
injuring-- whenever the
space shuttle was going up,

00:03:30.470 --> 00:03:33.030 align:middle line:84%
if any solar events were
occurring, especially

00:03:33.030 --> 00:03:36.070 align:middle line:84%
during the time
of solar maximum,

00:03:36.070 --> 00:03:38.720 align:middle line:84%
even as it was rising
up the Bell Curve,

00:03:38.720 --> 00:03:40.470 align:middle line:90%
they would stand down.

00:03:40.470 --> 00:03:43.830 align:middle line:84%
There have been two incidents
where the shuttle was

00:03:43.830 --> 00:03:47.680 align:middle line:84%
in flight and solar
flare erupted.

00:03:47.680 --> 00:03:51.420 align:middle line:84%
They have a special compartment
in the space shuttle

00:03:51.420 --> 00:03:53.899 align:middle line:84%
that the astronauts go
in there for protection.

00:03:53.899 --> 00:03:56.440 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: If-- if it that were to
happen when they're in space.

00:03:56.440 --> 00:03:57.055 align:middle line:90%
>>MITCH: It did happen.

00:03:57.055 --> 00:03:58.190 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: And it did happen.

00:03:58.190 --> 00:04:01.074 align:middle line:84%
>>MITCH: And the same
with the space station.

00:04:01.074 --> 00:04:02.740 align:middle line:84%
The space station is
not going anywhere,

00:04:02.740 --> 00:04:04.380 align:middle line:84%
it's staying up
there, and they also

00:04:04.380 --> 00:04:06.790 align:middle line:84%
have a special
compartment which they've

00:04:06.790 --> 00:04:09.497 align:middle line:84%
had to use several times when
the solar flares come our way.

00:04:09.497 --> 00:04:10.330 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:04:10.330 --> 00:04:12.260 align:middle line:84%
One of our Facebook
questions is coming in--

00:04:12.260 --> 00:04:15.710 align:middle line:84%
if you can see these solar
flares from a telescope.

00:04:15.710 --> 00:04:16.790 align:middle line:90%
>>MITCH: Yes, you can.

00:04:16.790 --> 00:04:20.120 align:middle line:84%
There are several ground based
telescopes, fairly large,

00:04:20.120 --> 00:04:25.160 align:middle line:84%
that people use, mostly in
the professions-- universities

00:04:25.160 --> 00:04:27.620 align:middle line:90%
or professional astronomers.

00:04:27.620 --> 00:04:31.220 align:middle line:84%
There, at times, again,
depending on the skies

00:04:31.220 --> 00:04:35.400 align:middle line:84%
and if you're in a dark place,
and what phase the solar cycle

00:04:35.400 --> 00:04:40.474 align:middle line:84%
is in, smaller telescopes
have been known to see that.

00:04:40.474 --> 00:04:41.390 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: To grasp that.

00:04:41.390 --> 00:04:44.600 align:middle line:84%
So when have we seen these in
history, these solar flares

00:04:44.600 --> 00:04:46.780 align:middle line:84%
and their different sizes
you're talking about?

00:04:46.780 --> 00:04:48.410 align:middle line:84%
>>MITCH: Well, it
happens all the time.

00:04:48.410 --> 00:04:52.450 align:middle line:84%
It goes on an 11-year
cycle which takes you

00:04:52.450 --> 00:04:56.430 align:middle line:84%
from a minimum to a maximum,
that's 11 years, and then

00:04:56.430 --> 00:04:59.270 align:middle line:84%
another 11 years to go
from maximum to minimum.

00:04:59.270 --> 00:05:04.010 align:middle line:10%
So really it's a 22-year cycle--
11 years up, approximately,

00:05:04.010 --> 00:05:05.680 align:middle line:10%
and 11 years down.

00:05:05.680 --> 00:05:09.250 align:middle line:10%
Right now, we are
at solar maximum,

00:05:09.250 --> 00:05:10.600 align:middle line:10%
or coming very close to it.

00:05:10.600 --> 00:05:12.974 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: We're at one of the
peaks of the cycle right now?

00:05:12.974 --> 00:05:15.570 align:middle line:10%
>>MITCH: We're at one of
the peaks of the cycle.

00:05:15.570 --> 00:05:22.855 align:middle line:10%
In cycle-- which is
cycle 24, and cycle 23

00:05:22.855 --> 00:05:26.350 align:middle line:10%
it showed much larger
and more significant.

00:05:26.350 --> 00:05:29.560 align:middle line:84%
There were solar flares,
several X-Class flares,

00:05:29.560 --> 00:05:34.430 align:middle line:84%
and one that happened on
November 3, 2003, that

00:05:34.430 --> 00:05:38.550 align:middle line:84%
literally had to have
the space weather

00:05:38.550 --> 00:05:41.790 align:middle line:84%
center, NOAA, recalibrate
their instruments.

00:05:41.790 --> 00:05:45.716 align:middle line:84%
It literally pegged
their instruments

00:05:45.716 --> 00:05:46.840 align:middle line:90%
because it was so powerful.

00:05:46.840 --> 00:05:51.750 align:middle line:84%
They went up to X10 at the
time, this one was an X45.

00:05:51.750 --> 00:05:52.250 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:05:52.250 --> 00:05:54.770 align:middle line:84%
>>MITCH: Largest one in
history, but that's subjective.

00:05:54.770 --> 00:05:57.590 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: What impact did that
make on Earth at the time?

00:05:57.590 --> 00:06:00.820 align:middle line:84%
>>MITCH: Luckily enough,
that happened to just

00:06:00.820 --> 00:06:03.210 align:middle line:84%
be rotating around the
eastern limb of the sun,

00:06:03.210 --> 00:06:08.590 align:middle line:84%
so if you-- as you can see the
screen-- looking at the sun,

00:06:08.590 --> 00:06:10.050 align:middle line:84%
for example, that
solar flare you

00:06:10.050 --> 00:06:13.050 align:middle line:84%
see on your screen, that
is the eastern limb,

00:06:13.050 --> 00:06:15.750 align:middle line:90%
that part of the curve.

00:06:15.750 --> 00:06:18.690 align:middle line:84%
I'm sorry, that's
the western limb.

00:06:18.690 --> 00:06:22.050 align:middle line:84%
When we're looking at
the sun, it's opposite,

00:06:22.050 --> 00:06:26.500 align:middle line:84%
so the right side would be west,
which would typically be east,

00:06:26.500 --> 00:06:29.900 align:middle line:90%
and the left side would be east.

00:06:29.900 --> 00:06:32.470 align:middle line:84%
So it was just rotating around
eastern limb of the sun,

00:06:32.470 --> 00:06:36.620 align:middle line:84%
so it didn't have the
full force towards Earth

00:06:36.620 --> 00:06:39.010 align:middle line:90%
when that X45 went off.

00:06:39.010 --> 00:06:43.200 align:middle line:84%
If it had, it probably
would been every bit as bad

00:06:43.200 --> 00:06:51.410 align:middle line:84%
as what's called the Keridan
Event, which was, I believe,

00:06:51.410 --> 00:06:52.550 align:middle line:90%
1857.

00:06:52.550 --> 00:06:53.910 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: And what happened?

00:06:53.910 --> 00:06:55.960 align:middle line:84%
>>MITCH: It was so
powerful that at the time,

00:06:55.960 --> 00:06:58.680 align:middle line:84%
there weren't telephones, but
the telegraph people that--

00:06:58.680 --> 00:07:02.060 align:middle line:84%
dot, dot, dot, dot,
dot-- it knocked out

00:07:02.060 --> 00:07:06.040 align:middle line:84%
several of the lines
or the power lines,

00:07:06.040 --> 00:07:10.830 align:middle line:84%
and on occasion, it would
hit the telegraph station,

00:07:10.830 --> 00:07:12.572 align:middle line:90%
setting it on fire.

00:07:12.572 --> 00:07:13.530 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh my goodness.

00:07:13.530 --> 00:07:16.831 align:middle line:84%
>>MITCH: If it were to happen
today, I don't know what--

00:07:16.831 --> 00:07:19.080 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So it literally
penetrated the magnetic field?

00:07:19.080 --> 00:07:21.150 align:middle line:84%
>>MITCH: It literally
penetrated the lines

00:07:21.150 --> 00:07:26.530 align:middle line:84%
and traveled down the lines
right into the compartment,

00:07:26.530 --> 00:07:29.900 align:middle line:84%
lighting the paper--
telegraph paper-- on fire.

00:07:29.900 --> 00:07:31.800 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So tell us
how this exactly

00:07:31.800 --> 00:07:34.970 align:middle line:84%
affects the Earth's core
when these particles come

00:07:34.970 --> 00:07:39.970 align:middle line:84%
into and penetrate through
the Earth's magnetic field.

00:07:39.970 --> 00:07:41.730 align:middle line:84%
>>MITCH: What
happens is the Earth

00:07:41.730 --> 00:07:45.580 align:middle line:84%
has an inner core
and an outer core.

00:07:45.580 --> 00:07:48.930 align:middle line:84%
The inner core is solid--
iron, if you will,

00:07:48.930 --> 00:07:53.690 align:middle line:84%
iron, magnesium-- the
outer core is liquid.

00:07:53.690 --> 00:07:57.440 align:middle line:84%
They call it a dipole theory, so
it's like a magnetic bar that's

00:07:57.440 --> 00:08:02.340 align:middle line:84%
in the middle of Earth, so when
the charged particles come,

00:08:02.340 --> 00:08:04.770 align:middle line:84%
and it it's Earth directed,
it hits the Earth's

00:08:04.770 --> 00:08:07.750 align:middle line:84%
magnetic field, most of
the charged particles

00:08:07.750 --> 00:08:10.240 align:middle line:84%
are deflected because
of our magnetic field,

00:08:10.240 --> 00:08:14.080 align:middle line:84%
and they kind of warp
around the Earth,

00:08:14.080 --> 00:08:16.040 align:middle line:84%
so there's kind of
a tail behind it.

00:08:16.040 --> 00:08:18.514 align:middle line:84%
Some charged
particles penetrate,

00:08:18.514 --> 00:08:20.430 align:middle line:84%
and that's where the
problems are, in addition

00:08:20.430 --> 00:08:21.440 align:middle line:90%
to the satellites.

00:08:21.440 --> 00:08:24.590 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: OK, so now, when those
charged particles penetrate

00:08:24.590 --> 00:08:27.010 align:middle line:84%
and they turn into
kind of a funnel, what

00:08:27.010 --> 00:08:28.920 align:middle line:84%
does that look
like in our galaxy?

00:08:28.920 --> 00:08:30.600 align:middle line:84%
What is that--
what happens, what

00:08:30.600 --> 00:08:33.274 align:middle line:84%
experience happens
in our galaxy?

00:08:33.274 --> 00:08:34.690 align:middle line:84%
>>MITCH: Interesting
you ask that,

00:08:34.690 --> 00:08:37.559 align:middle line:84%
because not a lot of
people are aware of that.

00:08:37.559 --> 00:08:39.830 align:middle line:90%
This is breaking news.

00:08:39.830 --> 00:08:42.600 align:middle line:84%
This may be, at
most, one week old.

00:08:42.600 --> 00:08:43.350 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, good.

00:08:43.350 --> 00:08:46.290 align:middle line:90%
>>MITCH: This is cutting edge.

00:08:46.290 --> 00:08:50.690 align:middle line:84%
Astrophysicists, because of
the new instruments we have,

00:08:50.690 --> 00:08:54.160 align:middle line:84%
the new spacecraft we have, the
new satellites that we have,

00:08:54.160 --> 00:08:57.080 align:middle line:84%
we now have information
we've never had before.

00:08:57.080 --> 00:09:01.920 align:middle line:84%
They just published their
findings, their latest research

00:09:01.920 --> 00:09:06.900 align:middle line:84%
data, that does show
a direct causal affect

00:09:06.900 --> 00:09:10.040 align:middle line:84%
pf our galaxy, Milky
Way, and the sun.

00:09:10.040 --> 00:09:12.710 align:middle line:84%
That has not been
presented before.

00:09:12.710 --> 00:09:15.520 align:middle line:84%
Now people-- many
of the scientists--

00:09:15.520 --> 00:09:19.220 align:middle line:84%
had known about the
sun- connection,

00:09:19.220 --> 00:09:24.176 align:middle line:84%
but they usually described it
in descriptions of climate.

00:09:24.176 --> 00:09:28.580 align:middle line:84%
Climate is in measurements
of months, years, decades,

00:09:28.580 --> 00:09:29.860 align:middle line:90%
hundreds of years.

00:09:29.860 --> 00:09:34.160 align:middle line:84%
Weather is measured in
minutes, hours, and days.

00:09:34.160 --> 00:09:36.630 align:middle line:84%
That's changed in
the last five years,

00:09:36.630 --> 00:09:40.050 align:middle line:84%
partly due to my research
and equation, which took it

00:09:40.050 --> 00:09:43.050 align:middle line:84%
from looking at the causal
effect from the sun,

00:09:43.050 --> 00:09:45.930 align:middle line:84%
such as these charged
particles, and trying

00:09:45.930 --> 00:09:49.000 align:middle line:84%
to measure in
decades, to asking,

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:51.700 align:middle line:84%
is there an immediate
causal effect?

00:09:51.700 --> 00:09:56.730 align:middle line:84%
There is-- the solar
flare acts like a spike.

00:09:56.730 --> 00:10:00.980 align:middle line:84%
That's the first shot of charged
particles that shoots out.

00:10:00.980 --> 00:10:05.306 align:middle line:84%
That could reach the Earth in
eight minutes-- that's fast.

00:10:05.306 --> 00:10:09.940 align:middle line:84%
The one that does more damage
is what follows the solar flare.

00:10:09.940 --> 00:10:12.260 align:middle line:84%
That's called a
coronal mass ejection.

00:10:12.260 --> 00:10:16.330 align:middle line:84%
It's kind of like a cloud of
plasma, of charged particles.

00:10:16.330 --> 00:10:21.090 align:middle line:84%
That follows-- that takes
24 to 48 hours to reach us,

00:10:21.090 --> 00:10:23.370 align:middle line:84%
and that's what knocks
out the power grids.

00:10:23.370 --> 00:10:25.820 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: OK, so that then
penetrates what you say--

00:10:25.820 --> 00:10:29.500 align:middle line:84%
the magnetic field, and then it
goes to the core of the Earth

00:10:29.500 --> 00:10:33.180 align:middle line:84%
and then emanates out in
terms of plate tectonics and--

00:10:33.180 --> 00:10:35.970 align:middle line:84%
>>MITCH: That's very
close-- very close to that.

00:10:35.970 --> 00:10:38.330 align:middle line:84%
What creates the
magnetic field to begin

00:10:38.330 --> 00:10:43.560 align:middle line:84%
with is the Earth's core,
so it's already there,

00:10:43.560 --> 00:10:46.780 align:middle line:84%
but when those charged particles
hit that barrier already,

00:10:46.780 --> 00:10:48.155 align:middle line:84%
then there's kind
of a feedback--

00:10:48.155 --> 00:10:49.010 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK, I see.

00:10:49.010 --> 00:10:50.650 align:middle line:10%
